  <div id="reading-panel" class="tab-panel active">

    <div class="q-card" data-correct="B">
      <div class="q-number">Question 1</div>
      <div class="q-skill">Information and Ideas / Command of Evidence</div>
      <div class="q-passage">In many high-altitude ecosystems, soil nutrient availability acts as a strict constraint on plant biomass. Ecologist Dr. Elena Vance hypothesized that specific subalpine cushion plants actively alter their immediate substrate chemistry, creating localized microenvironments that facilitate the survival of neighboring, less-hardy flora.</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which finding, if true, would most directly support Dr. Vance's hypothesis?</div>
      <ul class="q-options">
        <li><button onclick="checkAnswer(this,'A','reading')">A) Subalpine cushion plants exhibit faster growth metrics when positioned near rocky outcrops than when situated in deep valley soils.</button></li>
        <li><button onclick="checkAnswer(this,'B','reading')">B) Soil samples gathered directly beneath cushion plants reveal significantly higher concentrations of bioavailable nitrogen than samples gathered two meters away.</button></li>
        <li><button onclick="checkAnswer(this,'C','reading')">C) Neighboring flora species located far from cushion plants display an increased reliance on deep taproot structures to secure water reserves.</button></li>
        <li><button onclick="checkAnswer(this,'D','reading')">D) Genetic analysis shows no significant evolutionary divergence between subalpine cushion plants and low-altitude variants.</button></li>
      </ul>
      <div class="q-explanation"><strong>Correct Answer: B.</strong> The hypothesis states cushion plants actively alter substrate chemistry to help neighboring plants. Finding elevated bioavailable nitrogen directly beneath cushion plants confirms both the chemical alteration and its localized effect — directly supporting the hypothesis. The other choices address cushion plant growth (A), distant plant behavior (C), or genetics (D), none of which address the substrate chemistry claim.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="q-card" data-correct="A">
      <div class="q-number">Question 2</div>
      <div class="q-skill">Craft and Structure / Words in Context</div>
      <div class="q-passage">The corporate governance committee insisted that the executive's record, far from being completely unblemished, was actually marked by strategic omissions. Yet, because those omissions never technically violated local statutes, the final compliance report described his tenure as entirely _______.</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word?</div>
      <ul class="q-options">
        <li><button onclick="checkAnswer(this,'A','reading')">A) licit</button></li>
        <li><button onclick="checkAnswer(this,'B','reading')">B) peerless</button></li>
        <li><button onclick="checkAnswer(this,'C','reading')">C) anomalous</button></li>
        <li><button onclick="checkAnswer(this,'D','reading')">D) explicit</button></li>
      </ul>
      <div class="q-explanation"><strong>Correct Answer: A.</strong> The sentence establishes a contrast with "Yet": despite the omissions, they "never technically violated local statutes," so the report called his tenure lawful. "Licit" means lawful or permissible — a precise fit. "Peerless" means unmatched (doesn't fit the legal context), "anomalous" means irregular (contradicts the report's tone), and "explicit" means clearly stated (irrelevant here).</div>
