      <ul class="q-options">
        <li><button onclick="checkAnswer(this,'A','math')">A) \(\dfrac{5}{12}\)</button></li>
        <li><button onclick="checkAnswer(this,'B','math')">B) \(\dfrac{13}{5}\)</button></li>
        <li><button onclick="checkAnswer(this,'C','math')">C) \(\dfrac{12}{13}\)</button></li>
        <li><button onclick="checkAnswer(this,'D','math')">D) \(\dfrac{5}{13}\)</button></li>
      </ul>
      <div class="q-explanation"><strong>Correct Answer: C.</strong> If \(\sin\theta = \dfrac{5}{13}\), the opposite side is 5 and the hypotenuse is 13. Use the Pythagorean theorem: adjacent \(= \sqrt{13^2 - 5^2} = \sqrt{169 - 25} = \sqrt{144} = 12\). Therefore \(\cos\theta = \dfrac{12}{13}\). This is the classic 5-12-13 right triangle — one of the Pythagorean triples worth memorizing for the SAT.</div>
    </div>

